{
  "texts": [
    "Among them, the fact that -D is positive definite is of fundamental importance for most applications (see Remark A.9, (ii) below).Let X D be the vector field on N whose flow is the one-parameter subgroup of automorphisms (η t) ⊂ Aut(N) satisfying (η t) * = exp(tD) for all t ∈ R. Notice that X D is nothing but the fundamental vector field corresponding to D for the action of Aut(N) on N. This is an example of a linear vector field, since in exponential coordinates exp: 𝔫 → N, X D is simply given by 𝔫 ∋ U → DU.Proposition A.4.",
    "Let (N, h) be a nilsoliton with soliton derivation D. Then, any soliton vector field X is of the form X D + Y R, where Y R is any right-invariant vector field on N, and D ∈ Der(𝔫) is such that 1 2 ( D + DT) = D. Moreover', any such X has a unique zero on N. Proof.",
    "By the proof of Proposition A.2, it follows that X D is a soliton vector field.",
    "Any two soliton vector fields differ by a Killing field, and by [Wil82], for a left-invariant metric on a nilpotent Lie group, these are always of the form X D1 + Y R, where Y R is right-invariant and X D1 is linear, with D 1 ∈ Der(𝔫) a h-skewsymmetric derivation.",
    "Hence, any soliton vector field is of the form X D +X D1 +Y R = X D +Y R, D:= D +D 1, and the first part of the statement follows.Applying L X D 1 to the soliton equation yields0 = L X D 1 L X D h = L [X D 1,X D] h = L X [D 1,D] h.Then X [D1,D] is a Killing field vanishing at e, thus of the form X D2 with D 2 a skew-symmetric derivation."
  ]
}